Class StringLengthInRangeConstraint

java.lang.Object

          org.araneaframework.uilib.form.constraint.StringLengthInRangeConstraint
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable, Constraint
public class StringLengthInRangeConstraint
extends BaseFieldConstraint<String,String>

A Constraint that constrains the input length of a FormElement.

Usually form element text controls already have this kind of constraint built-in. However, when a text control does not have it built-in, this constraint can be used instead.

Author:
Jevgeni Kabanov (ekabanov@araneaframework.org)

Constructor Detail

StringLengthInRangeConstraint

public StringLengthInRangeConstraint()
Initializes this constraint without binding it with a field. Use setRangeStart(int) and setRangeEnd(int) to specify valid length criteria, or this constraint will always invalidate the data.

StringLengthInRangeConstraint

public StringLengthInRangeConstraint(FormElement<String,String> field)
Creates a String length constraint for given form element. Use setRangeStart(int) and setRangeEnd(int) to specify valid length criteria, or this constraint will always invalidate the data.

Parameters:
field - The form element to be constrained.

StringLengthInRangeConstraint

public StringLengthInRangeConstraint(int rangeStart,
                                     int rangeEnd)
Creates the constraint, and initializes the allowed length range. The minimum length must be less than the maximum length allowed, or the constraint never validates.

If the minimum length is less than 1 then it is not checked.

Parameters:
rangeStart - The minimum allowed length of the value.
rangeEnd - The maximum allowed length of the value.
Method Detail

validateConstraint

protected void validateConstraint()
Checks that the length of the field value is in constrained boundaries.

Specified by:
validateConstraint in class BaseConstraint

setRangeEnd

public void setRangeEnd(int rangeEnd)
Specifies the new maximum length for the value. It must be greater than the minumum length allowed, or the constraint never validates.

Parameters:
rangeEnd - The new maximum length for the value.

setRangeStart

public void setRangeStart(int rangeStart)
Specifies the new minimum length for the value. It must be less than the maximum length allowed, or the constraint never validates.

If this value is less than 1 then the minimum length is not checked.

Parameters:
rangeStart - The new minimum length for the value.
